To draw a chessboard from a FEN notation in LaTeX, you'll need to use a combination of packages: `tikz`, `tikzlibrary-shapes`, and `fp` (for calculations). Here's the LATEX code to achieve this:

**Required packages:**
```latex
\documentclass{article}
\usepackage{tikz}
\usetikzlibrary{shapes.geometric}
\usepackage{fp}
```
**Custom styles and functions:**
```latex
% Define styles for squares, ranks, and files
\tikzstyle{chesssquare} = [draw, thin, rectangle, minimum size=1cm]
\tikzstyle{rank} = [gray, very thin]
\tikzstyle{file} = [gray, very thin]

% Function to convert FEN rank and file numbers to coordinates
\FPset{\squarewidth}{1cm}
\newcommand{\fenpos}[2]{%
  (\FPmul{\x}{#1}{\squarewidth} - \FPmul{\y}{8-#2}{\squarewidth})%
}

% Function to draw a chessboard from FEN notation
\newcommand{\drawchessboard}[1]{%
  \begin{tikzpicture}
    \foreach \i in {1,2,...,8} {
      \draw [rank] (\fenpos{0}{\i}) -- (\fenpos{8,\i});
      \draw [file] (\fenpos{\i,1}) -- (\fenpos{\i,8});
    }
    \foreach \i in {1,2,...,8} {
      \foreach \j in {1,2,...,8} {
        \path (\fenpos{\i}{\j}) node [chesssquare, minimum size=\squarewidth] {};
        % Add your FEN piece notation here (e.g., \node at (\fenpos{\i}{\j}) {\small \blackman};)
      }
    }
  \end{tikzpicture}
}

% Example usage: Draw a chessboard from a FEN string
\def\FEN{rnbqkbnr/pppppppp/8/8/8/8/PPPPPPPP/RNBQKBNR w KQkq - 0 1}
\begin{document}
\begin{center}
\drawchessboard{\FEN}
\end{center}
\end{document}
```
